This is mostly off topic, so I'll try to get my point across as briefly as possible.<br>
<br>
/sigh....<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;1) In the first GulF War 200,000 iraqi troops were massacred, and yes MASSACRED is the appropriate word because it was a military pushover and wipe out on a truly grand scale (due to the skill and equipment of the allies).&quot;<br>
<br>
You're right to a point.  I really don't know the number that were killed, but it was a whole hell of a lot.  The coup de gras was the &quot;highway of death&quot; incedent.  That added to the fact that we had achieved our objective of ousting Iraq from Kuwait (let's not forget, Iraq was in INVADING ARMY) are what caused Colin Powell to pull the plug on the operation short of actually taking Baghdad.  He'd seen enough.<br>
<br>
However...you fail to mention the 60 some-odd thousand PoW's we took in, fed, clothed and sheltered.  PoW's that were being held in their fighting positions at gunpoint.  They were begging to surrender.  Hell, they were surrendering to CNN crews.<br>
<br>
You also fail to realize that soldiers do not think on such grand terms when they're being shot at.  All they know is that they're going to shoot the other guy first.  They don't really care that their enemies are being forced to fight.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
&quot;You didnt see many images of the effects, did you?&quot;<br>
<br>
I had many friends in the Army who were veterans of Desert Storm.  Most of them have pictures, and they like to share.  I've seen the closeups from the &quot;highway of death&quot;.  Bodies charred in their vehicles, you can see where some were trying to crawl away...the pictures are more than I know how to put into words.  But you have to remember that the people that died there were trying to escape into Iraq quite literally with the booty they'd pillaged from Kuwait.  Not to mention all of the military weaponry they'd have just turned around and pointed at us had we not destroyed it.<br>
<br>
I've also seen pictures from the ground fighting.  Yes, it was horrible.  But you cannot blame the nations that took part in desert storm.  That is, unless, you blame Iraq.  The Iraqis were resisting.  Saddam Hussein refused to back down and unfortunately his soldiers paid the price. <br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;2) Who put Saddam Hussein, the Ayatollah Homenei and other various loonies in power across the world in the first place, hm?&quot;<br>
<br>
I must admit I don't know <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  .  Although I'm sure I can guess where this is going.  Don't tell me...let me research it and get back to you <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;3) Is it REALLY Saddam Hussein? With amount of stand ins he's had, who knows if hes alive, or merely a &quot;bogeyman&quot; used by clever manipulators?&quot;<br>
<br>
Does it matter?  It's sort of like Orwell's &quot;Big Brother&quot;.  Even if he doesn't really exist, one could argue that Saddam Hussein is an &quot;institution&quot; that needs to be toppled.  Unfortunately, while he exists (in whatever form), it is quite likely that the only way this can be accomplished is through force.  I honestly hope, as you do, that he'll just pack up and leave...but that opens a whole other can of worms.  We can get into that later if you'd like.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;If he goes, will the whole arab world go extremist?&quot;<br>
<br>
This is a very good question, and one that I hope Belarkan will address.  I honestly do not know.  It is a common argument that is used here in the US as well, but one for which I've never heard any real substantiation.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;5) Like America doesnt have weapons of mass destruction, duh? While the Army almost certaily has got rid of chem and bio weapons, other US agencies have certainly been a tad shady about such stuff. *cough, CIA recruiting folk with bio-science degress...*&quot;<br>
<br>
I've no doubt the US military has them.  The difference is that the US has not used chem warfare since WWI, when all the other countries used them.  Saddam Hussein has used them within the last 20 years on his own people.<br>
<br>
I think it would make sense for the CIA to hire such people when we are on the brink of a war with a country that we at least know HAS possessed weapons of mass destruction and HAS used them in the past.  Perhaps they are the agents providing the proof that Washington claims it has(?).  My point is that I can come up with reasons just as easily as you can, and the fact is that neither of us will likely ever know.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;(oh CHina is the SECOND world Super Power today ya know)&quot;<br>
<br>
This is debatable <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  .  China very easily COULD be a super power would they change their social policies to better reflect those of the rest of the world.<br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
Silverblade: &quot;7) Terrorism is the new COMMIE RED THREAT! and using that America is degenerating into a police state, or would you deny a ton of the liberties Americans, quite rightly fought for, are being quashed, and maybe abused by the state against its very citizens? Dont you have a sneaking feeling that the new homeland security agency maybe a new Gestapo?&quot;<br>
<br>
While I've yet to be visited by jack-booted government thugs (or even see any in public), I will admit that I think the Bush administration is walking the line of what is constitutional and what is not in a few very select circumstances (enemy combatants that happen to be US citizens, for example).  The PoW's in Cuba are another story.  They are being taken care of according to the Geneva Conventions and that is enough.  <br>
<br>
Fortunately for us, we have (some will disagree, of course) what I consider to be a very wise and level headed supreme court that has not hesitated in the past to excercise its power when necessary.<br>
