<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Only two things are infinite: the Universe and human stupidity, and I'm not sure about the former.&quot; -- Albert Einstein</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caenn>Caenn</A> at: 2/16/03 1:13:43 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kannt00>Kannt00</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#333333>(2/16/03 4:26:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=90>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Forget morality, SHOULD we even go into war!?</span><hr size=1> The authoritarian Iraqi government, if left alone, is a danger to its citizens, its neighbours and American national security.  I believe we all can agree on this point.  I believe most people can also agree, consequently, that Saddam must be *permanently* disarmed.<br>
<br>
The relevant question, proceeding from these two points:  how can he best be kept disarmed, whilst minimising the loss of (especially civilian) life?<br>
<br>
So far there are two options.  One is war and the other is continued inspections.  According to the U.N. inspectors themselves, they can not perform their duties without complete cooperation from the Iraqi regime.  Today, they are getting good results, and have not turned up any WMD.  This is a new development:  for over a decade, the Iraqi regime has done everything in its power to thwart the U.N inspector's efforts.  For several years, Iraq kicked them out of the country entirely.  When the inspectors were there, they were denied access to important weapons sites and science personnel.<br>
<br>
What has changed?  Why are the inspectors suddenly able to perform their jobs?  Answer:  there is a military force capable of leveling the iraqi military on its borders.  This is do or die for Saddam.  <br>
<br>
However, that force can not be kept there indefinately.  The soldiers must attack soon or go home; keeping 200,000 plus men in the region is not an option for a plethora of reasons.<br>
<br>
When the soldiers go home, can anyone have faith that iraq will still cooperate with inspectors?  History says they will not.<br>
<br>
Iraq, as the second oil-richest country in the world, has access to vast capital.  Unhindered, they have the ability to build a huge military and aggressively develop WMD.  When this occurs (as it surely will, if the international community does not deter it from doing so) will america be able to muster the support to attack again, after having backed off on regime-change twice in a row?  I think not.  It is now or never.<br>
<br>
Looking at North Korea brandishing its WMD at the world today, one wishes the U.S. had been able to consolidate its victory in the Korean war, creating an entirely democratic penninsula.  This was not possible due to the resistance of China and the USSR.  But luckily Iraq has no such allies.  This is a unique opportunity to oust a militant, oppressive, murderous tyrant from power.  <br>
<br>
The objective is keeping Iraq free of weapons that will threaten its neighbours, citizens and the United States.  If a reasoned, practical proposal for bringing this about without war is proposed, one must certainly pursue it.  Unfortunately, I see no such proposals on the table at present.<br>
<br>
I'd write more but this computer is being dismantled so that I can build my new box!  This will have to do.<br>
<br>
Kannt <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=darkerplanes>DarkerPlanes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#333333>(2/16/03 7:53:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=91>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   heh</span><hr size=1> Well, your right Caenn, in the sense that my last post was not well thought out and was not clarified enough.  The result of too much beer and not enough sleep i suppose <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
In any case, what I said in my last post was pure conjecture.  It could happen, but then again, it might not happen.  Those are just possible scenarios that I threw onto the table to talk about.  While they could've been expressed better, my question still does remain, if either of those scenarios did happen (maybe you're right, they won't), would America be ready to see the results?  /shrug  <br>
<br>
Actually, I'm personally against going to war because I am a Libertarian, and also a Nationalist, and as a rule, I don't believe America has the right/responsibilty to be the World's policeman.  Rather, I believe that America should be the world's merchant and allow capitalism and its buisnesses to invest in the economies of other nations, which will cause their economy to grow.  I am a firm believer in globalization..<br>
<br>
I suppose the last reason why I am against the war is because I personally am not willing to go to war.  &quot;I will not fight, and because I won't fight, I shall not cast a vote for another man to fight in my place&quot; -That Guy From the Patriot.  That last reason is a selfish reason, I admit, but it also is a product of my personal morality.  If there was a war that I believed was just and necessary by my standards, I would gladly take up arms and fight.  But because I don't believe in the war, I will not fight, nor will I urge anyone else to fight in my stead.<br>
<br>
